Linked List and Java List

1 Implementation of Linked List

class ListNode {
  public int value; // any type
  public ListNode next; // this ListNode is a reference
  // public ListNode prev;
  public ListNode(int value) {
    this.value = value;
    this.next = null;
  }
}

ListNode head = new ListNode(3);
head.next = new ListNode(4);

2 Difference between Array and List

To represent sequence of elements: array/list

  • array: {1, 2, 3} - the elements are stored in consecutive memory.
[ 1 | 2 | 3 ]
  • list: {1, 2, 3} - the elements are not stored in consecutive space, but are connected by the pointer/references.
[ 1 | next ] head
       /
      /
     /
    /
   /
  V
[ 2 | next ]
       /
      /
     /
    /
   /
  V
[ 3 | next ]

For list, we need to always know where the “HEAD” is, so that we can traverse/find any elements in the list by iterating the “next” reference.

3 Array v.s. Linked List Comparison

  • Memory Layout
    • Array: consecutive allocated memory space, no overhead
    • Linked List: non-consecutive, overhead of multiple objects with the “next” reference
  • (Random) Access Time? - get the i-th element
    • Array: O(\(1\)), calculating the offset is O(\(1\)), e.g. int value = array[5];
    • Linked List: O(\(n\)) worst case, we can only traverse from the “HEAD”
  • Search Time (Non-sorted)?
    • Array: O(\(n\))
    • Linked List: (\(n\))
  • Search Time (Sorted)?
    • Array: O(\(\log(n)\)) - binary search
    • Linked List: O(\(n\))
    • Reason: random access time is different for array and list

4 Objects, Reference, null in Linked List Operations

class ListNode {
  public int value;
  public ListNode next;
  // public ListNode prev; -> Doubly Linked List, very powerful, covered later
  public ListNode(int value) {
    this.value = value;
    this.next = null;
  }
}

Let’s review this block of codes first:

ListNode current = null;
ListNode next = null;
current = new ListNode(0);
next = new ListNode(1);
ListNode temp = current;  // temp
current.next = next;  // 這步寫在了heap中, 可持續
current = current.next;

What is current, temp, next at this point finishing all the lines above?

  • current.value: 1
  • next.value: 1
  • temp.value: 0

Breakdown:

null: the reference is not pointed to any Object on the Heap. (null is a special value for reference)

  • Step 1
    1. Initialize to null, not pointing to any concrete object in the heap.
ListNode current = null;
ListNode next = null;

  • Step 2
    1. Allocate space on heap and create a new ListNode object with {value = 0, next = null}
    2. Return the object’s memory address as the value of reference.
current = new ListNode(0);

  • Step 3
next = new ListNode(1);

  • Step 4
    1. temp will be assigned the same value as current, which means temp is pointed to the same ListNode object where current is pointed to.
ListNode temp = current;

  • Step 5
    1. Dereferencing current to find the actual ListNode object, change the next field.
current.next = next;

  • Step 6
current = current.next;

What about we adding these two lines after? What would be the result?

  • Line 1
temp.next = temp.next.next; // temp.next = null; 不會有NPE
  • Line 2 (NPE!!!)
current.next = current.next.next; // NullPointerException!
// (current.next).next <-> null.next

5 Linked List Operations

5.1 length()

1 -> 2 -> 3 -> null

// written by student
public int length(ListNode head) {
  int counter = 0;
  ListNode temp = head;
  while(temp != null) {
    temp = temp.next;
    counter++;
  }
  return counter;
}

Or, we can just use head without temp. Because in Java, it’s pass by value, and the head is only a copy of the reference.

int length(ListNode head) {
  int length = 0;
  while (head != null) {
    length++;
    head = head.next;
  }
  return length;
}

5.2 get()

1 -> 2 -> 3 -> null

index = 0 -> return 1

index = 4 -> return null

// written by student
public ListNode get(ListNode head, int index) {
  ListNode current = head;
  int counter = index;
  while(current != null && counter >= 1) {
    current = current.next;
    counter--;
  }
  // DeMorgain's Law: curr == null || counter < 1 (counter == 0)
  // post-processing
  return current == null ? null : current;
}
ListNode get(ListNode head, int index) {
  while (index > 0 && head != null) {
    head = head.next;
    index--;
  }
  return head;
}

5.3 appendHead()

ListNode appendHead(ListNode head, int value) {
  ListNode newHead = new ListNode(value);
  newHead.next = head;
  return newHead;
}

5.4 appendTail()

ListNode appendTail(ListNode head, int value) {
  // 1. head == null
  if (head == null) {
    return new ListNode(value);
  }
  // 2. head != null, find the last node in the list
  ListNode prev = head;
  while (prev.next != null) {
    prev = prev.next;
  }
  // exit the while loop when prev.next == null
  prev.next = new ListNode(value);
  return head;
}

head could be changed - we need to return the new head if changed

usually need to consider:

  • head == null: after the last node
  • head.next == null: on the last node

while loop: we need to understand what is the terminate condition

5.5 remove()

Assuming no duplicate values, 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> null, remove(2), result 1 -> 3 -> null

ListNode remove(ListNode head, int value) {
  // 1. head == null
  if (head == null) {
    return null;
  }
  else if (head.value == value) { // 2. remove head
    return head.next;
  }
  // 3.
  ListNode current = head;
  while(current.next != null && current.next.value != value) {
    current = current.next;
  }
  // out of the while loop, current.next == null || current.next.value == value
  if (current.next != null) {
    current.next = current.next.next;
  }
  return head;
}

6 LinkedList in Java

Backend by a doubly linked list, wrap the size, head and tail information.

class ListNode<E> {
  E e;
  private ListNode<E> prev;
  private ListNode<E> next;
}

class LinkedList<E> {
  private ListNode<E> head;
  private ListNode<E> tail;
  private int size;
  
  public E get(int index) {
    // traverse from the head and find the node at index
  }
  
  // ... other operations provided...
}
  • get(int index)
    • from the head/tail, traverse the list to get the element at index
  • set(int index, E e)
    • from the head/tail, traverse the list to get the element at index, and change it
  • add(int index, E e), add(E e)
    • at tail: append new node after tail and update tail to the new added node
    • at head: insert in front of the head, and update head to the new added node
    • at middle
  • remove(int index)
    • at head: update the head to head.next
    • at tail: update the tail to tail.prev
    • at middle: from head/tail, traverse the list to get the element at index, and remove it.
  • size()
    • Time: O(\(1\)), eager computation
  • isEmpty()
    • return size == 0;, 直接返回判斷的布爾值
List<Integer> list = new LinkedList<Integer>();

System.out.println(list.size());  // 0

list.add(1);  // add at end, {1}
System.out.println(list.size());  // 1

list.add(0, 2); // add at head, {2, 1}
System.out.println(list.size());  // 2

list.add(1, 3); // add at middle, {2, 3, 1}
System.out.println(list.get(1));  // 3
list.remove(1); // {2, 1}
System.out.println(list.set(0, 4)); // {4, 1}
System.out.println(list); // {4, 1}

6.1 E (Element)

  1. 裝什麽類型就寫什麽類型: LinkedList<Student> l = new LinkedList<>();
  2. Cannot be a primitive type (int: Integer, char: Character, boolean: Boolean, wrapper class)
  3. LinkedList<Student> l = new LinkedList<>();, <>: diamond operator, the same as left hand side. Supported by Java 7.

7 List Interface in Java

  • An ordered collection (sometimes called a sequence).
  • Lists can contain duplicate elements.

The user of a List generally has precise control over where in the list each element is inserted and can access elements by their index.

Provided functionalities (interfaces):

  • Random Access:
    • set(int index, E e)
    • get(int index)
    • add(int index, E e), add(E e)
    • remove(int index)
  • Search
  • Iterator
  • Range-view
  • Other useful methods:
    • isEmpty()
    • size()

Most popular implementation class: LinkedList, ArrayList.

8 Abstract Class, Interface

8.1 Semantics (語義) v.s. Implementations (實現)

Separate semantic and implementation: language specs define semantics, language implementations (such as JVM) defines the actual behavior of a program.

E.g., in real life: 菜譜 v.s. 做飯, 攻略 v.s. 打游戲

Semantically:

  1. int i = 0;
  2. i++;, now i = 1

In one implementation:

  1. Set i to be 0
  2. Read i, i = 0
  3. Perform 0 + 1 = 1
  4. Write new value 1 back to i’s memory location

The actual execution sequence varies (different JVMs, different architectures, etc.), but the “meaning” of the program remains unchanged.

8.2 Abstract Class and Interfaces

Both can have methods declared without implementation (abstract methods). “Protocol”

interface 貓 {
  public void 抓老鼠()
}
public class 黑貓 implements 貓 {
  public void 抓老鼠() {
    // 黑貓抓老鼠的姿勢
  }
}
public class 白貓 implements 貓 {
  public void 抓老鼠() {
    // 白貓抓老鼠的姿勢
  }
}
interface Dictionary {
  // index out of bound, it will return null
  public Integer get(int index);
}

// Dictionary myDict = new Dictionary(); Wrong! Interface cannot be used to instantiate an object

class DictionaryImpl implements Dictionary {
  @Override
  public Integer get(int index) {
    // ...
  }
}

Dictionary myDict = new DictionaryImpl();
myDict.get(100);

Abstract class/Interface: you cannot instantiate an object by abstract class or interface.

public int search(A a, int target) {
  return a.print();
}

interface A {
  public void print();
}

class B implements A {
  @Override
  public void print() {
    System.out.println("B");
  }
}

Good practice: Declare into a general type, initialize into a concrete type (Interfaces are also types):

List<Node> myList = new LinkedList<Node>();
myList.get(5);  // fine
myList.set(5, 7); // fine
myList.poll();  // not fine, because the method poll() is not belong to List, but other data structures (i.e. Queue)
  1. Preserve the general semantic of a List
    • Can only use methods in a List interface
    • Not to make any assumptions on implementation
    • Make sure interchangeable in future
  2. Provide concrete implementation by using LinkedList
    • Choose the best implementation for the current use case

Abstract Class Interface
1. Abstract class can have abstract and non-abstract methods. Interface can have only abstract methods.
2. Abstract class doesn’t support multiple inheritance. Interface supports multiple inheritance.
3. Abstract class can have final, non-final, static and non-static variables. Interface has only static and final variables.
4. Abstract class can have static methods, main method and constructor. Interface can’t have static methods, main method or constructor.
5. Abstract class can provide the implementation of interface. Interface can’t provide the implementation of abstract class.
6. The abstract keyword is used to declare abstract class. The interface keyword is used to declare interface.
